The '''2007 tuberculosis scare''' occurred when [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]] [[personal injury lawyer|personal-injury lawyer]] '''Andrew "Drew" Speaker''' flew from Atlanta, Georgia to Paris, France and on to Greece and then Italy before returning on a flight from Prague, Czech Republic to Montreal, Canada, where he crossed over the border and back into the United States while infected with [[multi-drug-resistant tuberculosis]].<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/conditions/05/31/tb.flight/index.html Border security scrutinized after TB patient slips in], CNN.com</ref><ref name=Brown>Emily Brown and Jeff Bliss, [http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=ajze0qn17uXM&refer=home "Border Agents Failed to Stop Man With Tuberculosis" (Update4)].</ref> The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] believed at the time that Speaker was suffering from [[extensively drug-resistant tuberculosis]] (XDR-TB). The incident sparked a debate in [[United States Congress|Congress]] on the failure of [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|federal customs agents]] to stop him.<ref name = Brown /> Upon Speaker's return to the United States, the CDC placed him under involuntary isolation (similar to [[quarantine]]) using a provision of the [[Public Health Service Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/sars/isolationquarantine.htm|title=Fact Sheet on Isolation and Quarantine|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=2007-06-03}}</ref><!-- Check the cite - Speaker is NOT under quarantine -->  With this action, Speaker became the first individual subjected to a CDC isolation order since 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/other/news/may3107tb.html|title=Odd twist in TB alert: Patient is TB researcher's son-in-law|publisher=CIDRAP|accessdate=2007-06-02| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070603154608/http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/other/news/may3107tb.html| archivedate= 3 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Background==
In January 2007, Speaker suffered a fall and went to the doctor, concerned that he had bruised a rib. Doctors X-rayed his chest and found an abnormality that required further testing.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}} Andrew Speaker was suspected of having TB when a positive [[Mantoux test|PPD test]] came back on March 2, 2007. His third CT scan was done on March 3 and a bronchoscopy was done on March 8. After 18 days of incubation the isolate was sent to CDC for confirmation of his susceptibility results that were done by the Georgia Department of Human Resources (DHR).

On March 28, 2007 his doctors and the health department believed the TB strain Speaker had was a resistant one and communicated this to the CDC. On May 1 the apparent MDR TB infection was discussed with the CDC lab by his doctors and they discussed discontinuing the treatment he was on at that time. On May 9 the suspicion of MDR TB was confirmed. A meeting was held with [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] Health Officials, his doctors, his fiancée and his father and father-in-law on May 10, 2007. At this time he was told that he was not contagious and not a threat to anyone{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} but that he would need to go to Denver for treatment. It would take a few weeks to arrange this. He was advised, or according to some accounts strongly recommended, not to travel.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}

==Travel Sequence==
On May 12, 2007, Speaker [[transatlantic flight|flew from the U.S.]] to [[Paris]]. On May 14, he flew on to [[Athens]] and, two days later, flew to the [[Aegean Islands|Aegean]] holiday island of [[Santorini]] for his wedding (Santorini's Mayor [[Angelos Roussos]], states that Speaker lacked the necessary paperwork for the civil ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/conditions/06/01/tb.flight/index.html?xid=rss-world |title=CNN story on wedding |publisher=Cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-08 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071212013325/http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/conditions/06/01/tb.flight/index.html?xid=rss-world |archivedate = 2007-12-12}}</ref>). Speaker then flew to [[Rome]] for his honeymoon.

Doctors say that only after Speaker left the United States did they realize he likely had [[extensively drug-resistant tuberculosis|XDR-TB]]. Speaker says that he was informed of MDR TB before leaving the country, and that while officials preferred him not to fly, they said that he was not a threat and was not required to wear a mask.<ref>[http://www.healthnewsdigest.com/news/Disease_420/Diagnosed_with_a_Rare_Form_of_Tuberculosis_-.shtml Andrew Speaker Says He's Being Unfairly Attacked] by Eve Conant, Newsweek, 2 Jun 2007. Accessed 2009-04-30.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5gwsNfXSk Archived] 2009-05-21.</ref> Once Speaker was in Europe, however, test results showed his strain of tuberculosis was even rarer than originally thought, leading public health officials to try to persuade Speaker to turn himself in to Italian health authorities.[http://www.cnn.com/2007/POLITICS/06/07/tb.borders/index.html] [http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=3344625&page=1] The CDC informed him that there were no options for the CDC to get him home, and that he would have to arrange private transportation. Speaker instead flew by commercial jet to [[Prague]] and then on to [[Montréal]].<ref name=Park>Park, Alice. [http://www.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1627159,00.html "The TB Scare: A Broken System?"] ''Time''. May 31, 2007.</ref> Both Speaker and his new wife claimed that, had they been offered transport, they would have accepted it and would have waited in Rome.<ref name=McPhee>Mike McPhee, [http://www.denverpost.com/sportscolumnists/ci_6037621 TB patient apologizes] ''Denver Post''. June 1, 2007. Accessed 2009-04-30.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5gwsOTpNW Archived] 2009-05-21.</ref> Speaker has also said that the CDC told him they were going to send officials to put him in Italian quarantine for up to two years, and that he was not told special transportation was arranged.<ref name = McPhee />  

Once in Montréal, Speaker rented a car and drove across the [[Canada – United States border]]. A Customs and Border Protection Officer failed to detain him at the frontier, disregarding a warning after he had passed Speaker's passport through the [[Treasury Enforcement Communications System]] (TECS)<ref name="Brown"/> to hold the traveler, wear a protective mask when dealing with him, and call health authorities because he "did not look sick".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.9news.com/news/article.aspx?storyid=71772 | publisher=Fox News | accessdate=2007-06-11 | title= Border agent fired after allowing TB patient into country}}</ref>

