==Tuberculosis case notes==
{{wikinewspar2|US tuberculosis patient moved to Denver hospital|US places man with TB under quarantine, launches search for contactees}}
On May 31, 2007, Speaker was moved from [[Grady Memorial Hospital]] in [[Atlanta]] to the [[National Jewish Medical and Research Center]] in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]], [[Colorado]], for further treatment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276613,00.html |title=Foxnews.com: TB Patient moved to Denver hospital, May 31, 2007 |publisher=Foxnews.com |date=Thursday, May       31, 2007 |accessdate=2008-11-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20081002135315/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276613,00.html| archivedate= 2 October 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

It was reported that Speaker's father-in-law, Robert C. Cooksey, works for the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] and is a [[Microbiology|microbiologist]] who has conducted research on [[tuberculosis]], according to his CDC biography posted on the agency's Web site.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/conditions/05/31/tb.flight/index.html |title=CNN web site: TB patient's name released; father-in-law works at CDC |publisher=Cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-08 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080308192527/http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/conditions/05/31/tb.flight/index.html |archivedate = 2008-03-08}}</ref>  However, Cooksey has never worked with the strain of tuberculosis Speaker has been diagnosed with.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}

Wearing a medical mask, Speaker was interviewed by [[Diane Sawyer]] on the June 1 edition of the American talk show ''[[Good Morning America]]'' on ABC and apologized to all passengers, explaining that he had not intended to endanger them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/OnCall/story?id=3231184&page=1 |title=ABCNews.com: TB Patient: "I Really Believed I Wasn't Putting People at Risk" June 1, 2007 |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20080929161834/http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/OnCall/story?id=3231184&page=1| archivedate= 29 September 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

According to an interview on [[Larry King Live]], Speaker said that he had not been told that there was any risk of transmitting the disease to others, nor did the May 10 letter recommending against his travel state this, which Speaker in any case had not received before leaving May 14.  His wife, with whom he lived for five months without precautions, remained uninfected.

==New diagnosis==
On July 4, 2007 the National Jewish Medical and Research Center announced, and the CDC confirmed, that Mr. Speaker's earlier diagnosis was incorrect and that he instead had [[multi-drug-resistant tuberculosis]] (MDR-TB), a more treatable form of tuberculosis.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/07/03/tb.speaker/index.html | publisher=CNN | accessdate=2007-07-04 | title=Doctors: TB traveler's diagnosis more treatable than thought | date=2007-07-04| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070712192138/http://www.cnn.com/2007/HEALTH/07/03/tb.speaker/index.html#cnnSTCVideo| archivedate= 12 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Isolation and law==
Before a Congressional hearing, Speaker and his father played audio recordings from CDC and Fulton County health officials which say he was not a danger to others.  He asked such questions on five recordings repeatedly and was given the same answers even after stating on two recordings that he was going out of the country and the CDC later admitted they were aware and waited until he had already left before taking further actions.

Speaker was in New York when the CDC served him with an isolation order but CDC director Julie Gerberding stated that the government was legally constrained prior to that order.  The federal statute granting quarantine authority allows isolation or quarantine but only for individuals coming into the country from a foreign country or territory.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1181207137498 | publisher=Law.com | accessdate=2007-06-08 | title=The Legal Questions Behind the TB Case}}</ref>

Georgia TB law may have required Speaker to be confined for two weeks and only allowed travel for medical appointments.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.physorg.com/news103981421.html | publisher=Physorg.com | accessdate=2007-07-18 | title=TB patient travel may have been illegal| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070826171751/http://www.physorg.com/news103981421.html| archivedate= 26 August 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>  A court confinement order can isolate a patient only after the infected patient ignores medical advice.  This method can be overridden by a declaration of public health emergency by the governor of Georgia.

On July 12, 2007 it was announced that seven Canadians and two Czechs will launch $1.3 million in civil lawsuits in Montreal. Eight were on the same flight as Andrew Speaker and one was a roommate of one of those on the same flight.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=D8QB9BV80&show_article=1 | publisher=Breitbart.com | accessdate=2007-07-12 | title=Nine File Suit Against TB-Infected Man}}</ref>

